export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>This final class chapter covers the three families where excited-state physics sets the value: wide- and ultrawide-bandgap (WBG/UWBG) semiconductors (SiC, GaN, β-Ga₂O₃, diamond, AlN), halide perovskites, and thermoelectrics. Their binding error mode is taxonomy mode 2 (excited states, §3.2), compounded by mode 5 (finite temperature). The lesson I take from this class is sharper than &quot;errors are large&quot;: <strong>the number that matches experiment is sometimes the least trustworthy number</strong>, because here agreement is repeatedly manufactured by cancellation between two wrong terms. All figures are verified as of 2026-07-17.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-1", "html": "<p>The records are real. LONGi's two-terminal perovskite–silicon tandem reached 34.85% (NREL-certified, April 2025)<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"65\">[65]</sup> and — as certified in July 2026, the newest data point in this report — 35.5% (ESTI), against a ~43% tandem theoretical limit (33.7% single-junction Shockley–Queisser).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"344\">[344]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"65\">[65]</sup> Oxford PV shipped the first commercial tandem modules (24.5%, 72-cell) in September 2024.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup> The counter-evidence sits beside the celebration by design: LONGi has no active tandem mass-production plan; Oxford PV's warranties run 10 years product / 20 years power against silicon's 25–30; perovskite capacity is ~1.5 GW against &gt;540 GW installed in 2025 — 0.3%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"344\">[344]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup> Washington is buying in too: a <span class=\"math\">$750M CHIPS preliminary memorandum for Wolfspeed's 200 mm SiC plant; up to $</span>1.5B for GlobalFoundries, including a Vermont GaN fab.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"67\">[67]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"347\">[347]</sup> Beijing's 15th Five-Year Plan (15FYP) names semiconductors for &quot;decisive breakthroughs.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"348\">[348]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"349\">[349]</sup> Capital and records are flowing into exactly the classes whose computed numbers are least trustworthy; that asymmetry is the opening.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-2-1", "html": "<p>The 2025 all-electron benchmark of Großmann et al. (472 materials, 21 functionals) puts the local density approximation's (LDA's) average gap underestimate at ~50%: ScN (experiment 1.1 eV) comes out semi-metallic, Ge-class narrow-gap semiconductors metallic at GGA (≈0 versus ~0.7 eV experiment), and metal/semiconductor classification itself flips between PAW and all-electron potentials.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup> The ladder out is priced for benchmarks, not screening: hybrids cost ≥10× LDA<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"350\">[350]</sup> and one to two orders more than PBE<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"351\">[351]</sup>; conventional GW scales as <span class=\"math\">$\\mathcal{O}(N^4)$</span> — &quot;several million CPU hours&quot; for one benchmark; vertex-free quasiparticle self-consistent GW (QSGW) over-corrects, overshooting gaps ~15% (mean error +0.55 eV).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup> Downstream, the labels beneath most ML gap models carry the same bias: Materials Project (PBE/+U) gaps run low by an average factor ~1.6 (mean absolute error, MAE, ~0.6 eV), with known insulators computed metallic — and MAPE-style leaderboards reward gap-underestimating methods.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"352\">[352]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup> A tandem top cell wants ±0.05 eV compositional gap targeting near 1.65–1.75 eV; against a factor-1.6 label floor, that screen is unscreenable as labeled.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-2-2", "html": "<p>Three such cancellations are documented verbatim. One-shot <span class=\"math\">$G_0W_0$</span>@LDA agrees with experiment because &quot;the LDA-induced over-screening and the RPA-induced under-screening compensate in a fortuitous way.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup> Scalar-relativistic DFT reproduces the MAPbI₃ gap only because the GGA underestimate cancels the missing spin–orbit coupling (SOC), a ~1 eV term: CsPbI₃'s 1.2 eV LDA gap drops 1.1 eV under SOC, and SOC-DFT undershoots MAPbI₃ at 0.60 eV where scalar-relativistic DFT gave 1.68.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"18\">[18]</sup> The cancellation is composition-fragile — across the CH₃NH₃(Pb,Sn)(I,Br,Cl)₃ family &quot;the good agreement for MAPbI3 is really a coincidence&quot; — and its non-systematic residue is inherited by one-shot and eigenvalue-self-consistent GW: the cheap fix does not rescue the cheap functional.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"43\">[43]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"353\">[353]</sup> Even the best method is implicated. Vertex-corrected QSGŴ's diamond gap of 5.64 eV matches the measured 5.5 eV &quot;only because the systematic band gap underestimation from the W-only vertex correction nearly cancels out the missing EPR gap reduction,&quot; diamond's electron-phonon renormalization (EPR) being ~0.4 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup> The damage extends past gaps: SOC rewrites MAPbI₃'s effective masses (0.73/0.36 → 0.17/0.28 <span class=\"math\">$m_0$</span>), so models built on scalar-relativistic band edges inherit wrong curvatures too.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"18\">[18]</sup> A model trained on &quot;accurate-looking&quot; numbers from these ladders learns a non-causal map.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-2-3", "html": "<p>Frozen-ion and harmonic treatments miss the term that closes the perovskite gap at operating temperature: anharmonic fluctuations at 300 K raise the quasiparticle gap by up to +0.7 eV, against 50 meV harmonically — with class-dependent sign, blue-shifting halides where oxides red-shift.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"354\">[354]</sup> Zero-point motion renormalizes even silicon's gap by −56.2 meV (5%)<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"355\">[355]</sup> and diamond's direct gap by up to ~0.6 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"356\">[356]</sup> Static-supercell GW, the community's standard operating procedure, is structurally blind to it. The same missing anharmonicity now sits inside the field's flagship thermal-transport success story.</p>\n<div class=\"pullbox\">\n<p><strong>Case box 12.1 — Boron arsenide: the unknown-unknown inside &quot;mature&quot; phonon theory.</strong></p>\n<p>Boron arsenide (BAs) is the cleanest quantified case of theory error in a parameter-free method. Three-phonon DFT Boltzmann-transport theory predicted a lattice thermal conductivity (κ_l) of ~2,200 W/m·K in 2013.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"357\">[357]</sup> Early defective crystals measured 200–400; four-phonon scattering theory cut the prediction to ~1,400 in 2017 — 4-phonon rates exceed 3-phonon rates for the heat-carrying acoustic modes at 5–10 THz — and 2018 <em>Science</em> measurements of 1,000–1,300 W/m·K landed on the revised theory.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"358\">[358]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"359\">[359]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"360\">[360]</sup> The field declared victory. Then the 2025 crystals arrived: the best samples measure ~2,100–2,200 W/m·K, above the ~1,500 W/m·K that 3+4-phonon theory allows, and with no tunable parameters left the authors write that &quot;our experimental result cannot be explained by existing theory and calls for new theoretical work.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"361\">[361]</sup></p>\n<p>I draw two lessons. First, the 2018 agreement was the misleading data point: theory matched experiment only because the crystals were as defective as the theory was incomplete — the residual's sign and magnitude flipped twice in a decade as samples improved. Second, ground truth drifts: c-BAs' widely reported ~1.5 eV gap proved 0.3 eV too low through impurity acceptors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"362\">[362]</sup> An ML κ model trained on 3-phonon-only labels inherits the same unknown-unknown, labeled as truth; unknown-unknowns live inside mature methods, not just exotic ones.</p>\n</div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-2-4", "html": "<p>Universal MLIPs (uMLIPs) carry a quantified phonon residue: one benchmark write-up tabulates maximum-phonon-frequency (ωmax) MAEs of 17–61 K (MACE-MP-0 61; SevenNet-0 38; Nequix-OAM 17; curvature-fine-tuned variants 10–12 K), consistent with the peer-reviewed finding of ~15% systematic softening, which maps through the <span class=\"math\">$v^2$</span> factor of κ_l into tens-of-percent conductivity error before anharmonic terms are sampled.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"82\">[82]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"81\">[81]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"363\">[363]</sup> Non-conservative direct-force models (ORB, eqV2-M) return &quot;very low quality phonons, often imaginary.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"81\">[81]</sup> For polar WBG materials the failure is structural: no uMLIP represents LO–TO splitting without ab initio Born-charge augmentation.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"364\">[364]</sup> Defect levels are worse: the mid-gap states that set dopability and quantum-emitter transitions swing an order of magnitude with the functional — PBE puts a carbon-defect-dominated gap in h-BN at 0.14 eV, HSE06 at 1.44 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"365\">[365]</sup> Against established experimental ionization energies (diamond: B acceptor ~0.37 eV, P donor ~0.6 eV, N donor ~1.7 eV), DFT's 0.1–1 eV defect-level error bars match the quantities under prediction; β-Ga₂O₃ has no viable p-type at any error bar.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"366\">[366]</sup></p>\n<p><strong>Table 12.1 — Verified error figures for WBG semiconductors, perovskites, and thermoelectrics (as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Error</th>\n<th>Verified magnitude (method)</th>\n<th>Where it bites</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>LDA gap underestimate</td>\n<td>~50% average, 472-material all-electron benchmark; ScN semi-metallic, Ge-class metallic <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup></td>\n<td>Every semilocal-gap screen</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Materials Project gap compression</td>\n<td>low ×~1.6 average; MAE ~0.6 eV; known insulators metallic (PBE/+U) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"352\">[352]</sup></td>\n<td>ML gap labels; tandem top-cell targeting</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Perovskite SOC term</td>\n<td>~1 eV gap reduction (CsPbI₃: 1.2 eV LDA → −1.1 eV with SOC) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"18\">[18]</sup></td>\n<td>Fortuitous SR-DFT accuracy; wrong band curvatures</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Thermal gap renormalization</td>\n<td>up to +0.7 eV at 300 K (anharmonic MD) vs 50 meV harmonic <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"354\">[354]</sup></td>\n<td>Operating-temperature gaps; phase stability</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>BAs lattice thermal conductivity</td>\n<td>theory 2,200 → ~1,400 (3+4-phonon) → ~2,100–2,200 W/m·K measured 2025; residual unexplained <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"361\">[361]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"358\">[358]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"357\">[357]</sup></td>\n<td>κ_l databases; thermal-management design</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>uMLIP phonon ωmax MAE</td>\n<td>17–61 K (MDR benchmark) + ~15% systematic softening; imaginary modes in non-conservative models <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"81\">[81]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"82\">[82]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"363\">[363]</sup></td>\n<td>Finite-T stability; κ_l; T-dependent gaps</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>No row is fatal alone; the rows stack on a single prediction. A tandem-absorber screen stacks the first four: a ~50% source bias, compressed ×1.6 into labels, masked by a ~1 eV SOC cancellation, then shifted +0.7 eV at operating temperature — against a ±0.05 eV design tolerance. A thermoelectric screen stacks the last two. The rows also differ in kind: two (Materials Project compression, ωmax) are label-floor problems, fixable by fidelity escalation; two (SOC, thermal renormalization) are missing-physics problems, fixable only by method change; one (BAs) is an open problem whose physics is not yet identified. That mix — cheap fixes, method fixes, one honest unknown — defines where an independent lab can promise accuracy and where it must promise only validated uncertainty.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-3", "html": "<p>The excited-state lever is an error-cancellation-free stack. The same 472-material benchmark that documents the cancellations documents the exit: vertex-corrected QSGŴ can &quot;reliably flag questionable experimental measurements&quot; (spread σ 0.45 eV); the cheaper QPG₀W₀ holds a 0.08 eV mean error; SOC-GW delivers MAPbI₃ at 1.67 eV against experiment.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"17\">[17]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"18\">[18]</sup> The method is proven — the cost is the blocker (vertex-level GW converged for only 101 of 171 small-cell materials), and absorbing cost is what ML does well. The phonon lever is derivative-matched fine-tuning: a single study reports that Phonon Fine-Tuning (PFT) — aligning MLIP energy Hessians with DFT force constants — cuts phonon-property errors 55% on average and improves Matbench-Discovery thermal-conductivity prediction from 0.446 to 0.306 κSRME, with fine-tuned models at 10–12 K ωmax MAE; purpose-built MLIPs trained on anharmonic Hamiltonians reproduce terms to fifth order.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"88\">[88]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"82\">[82]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"367\">[367]</sup> Every production run in this stack carries scoreboard Row 5's misspecification-aware UQ as its audit layer (§3.3). What I will not promise is the BAs residual, where the physics itself is missing.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-4", "html": "<p>The durability ledger binds as tightly as the error tables. Perovskite PV ships with 10-year product / 20-year power warranties against silicon's 25–30-year standard, at ~0.3% of manufacturing capacity; the field's current durability proof point is a 45-day outdoor demonstration (GCL, Dubai).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup> The degradation physics — moisture, heat, ion migration — is precisely the dynamic-disorder regime where frozen-lattice DFT and near-equilibrium MLIPs fail: computation is asked to predict metastable lifetimes with tools that cannot yet predict the room-temperature gap. β-Ga₂O₃'s 4.8 eV gap and ~8 MV/cm breakdown field are undercut by an anisotropic κ of 9.5–29 W/m·K, one to two orders below GaN (~150–210) and SiC (~270–400); a 2025 device review concedes that &quot;no Ga2O3 device reported to this day has achieved the performance expected from its material properties&quot; — a thermally limited plateau.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"368\">[368]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"366\">[366]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"369\">[369]</sup> Diamond leads every figure of merit, yet dopes brutally asymmetrically (shallow 0.37 eV boron acceptor; 1.7 eV nitrogen donor, unusably deep), and even its gap is matched only through the QSGŴ cancellation of §12.2.2. SiC's flagship is a bankruptcy: Wolfspeed filed Chapter 11 on 30 June 2025, emerged 29 September with debt cut ~<span class=\"math\">$6.5B → ~$</span>2B, and took a $698.6M Section 48D tax refund while its CHIPS grant remained undisbursed — amid a 30–50% wafer-price collapse (trade-press figures).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"370\">[370]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"371\">[371]</sup> Wrong gap, defect, and κ predictions now land in a market that punishes error; that raises, not lowers, the value of validated numbers.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-5", "html": "<p>Both governments fund manufacturing; neither funds the error audit. Washington pairs the CHIPS awards with DOE Solar Energy Technologies Office (SETO) programs: the thin-film opportunity (<span class=\"math\">$36M announced 2023; $</span>44M awarded 2024), whose PRIMES topic puts $3–20M per project into perovskite-tandem manufacturing, and SIPS-2024, which funds perovskite defect-quantification metrology.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"372\">[372]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"373\">[373]</sup> The program names encode this chapter's pain points — defects, stability, scale-up. Beijing's 15FYP mobilizes its whole-of-nation system for &quot;decisive breakthroughs&quot; in semiconductors under &quot;extraordinary measures,&quot; with R&amp;D growth ≥7%/yr and procurement preference for domestic innovation; Chinese pilot lines already lead perovskite scale-up (UtmoLight 1 GW, February 2025; GCL 200 MW).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"348\">[348]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"349\">[349]</sup> I draw no competition narrative from this. The observation is narrower: public money on both sides buys capacity and records, while the credibility layer — cancellation-free gaps, anharmonic κ, validated stability — remains unowned and small enough for an independent lab to matter in.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s12-6", "html": "<p>This class feeds two of the eleven discovery chains consolidated in Chapters 13–15. Chain 6: an error-cancellation-free excited-state stack (QSGW plus ML) → stable perovskite tandems and WBG devices → 35%+ solar and Ga₂O₃/diamond-class power electronics → cheaper energy and efficient grids; its anchors are this chapter's ~50% LDA error and ~1 eV SOC cancellation, its solved target right gaps for the right reasons at screening cost. Chain 11: anharmonicity-aware κ prediction → earth-abundant mid-temperature thermoelectrics → industrial and data-center waste-heat recovery; its anchor is the BAs anomaly, its target quantitative κ_l with four-phonon and higher channels included by default. Both chains route through Chapter 14's stability doctrine — §12.4's warranty ledger is the identify axis applied to this class — and both take their row in Chapter 13's matrix.</p>\n<p>My working rule, stated as the venture's screening policy: <strong>distrust any predicted gap that agrees with experiment unless the bookkeeping shows the spin–orbit, vertex, and electron-phonon terms explicitly accounted for</strong>; a matching number without that bookkeeping is two errors I have not yet found. Applied here, where agreement is cheapest and the physics slipperiest, the rule is the difference between selling validations and selling coincidences. Chapters 13–15 turn it into a matrix, a stability doctrine, and eleven chains.</p>\n" },
]
